[1] Date: Thur 1 March 2012
Source: The Packer [edited]
http://www.thepacker.com/fruit-vegetable-news/One-third-of-New-Zealand-kiwifruit-orchards-infected-with-vine-di-141066943.html?ref=943


One-third of New Zealand kiwifruit orchards has vine disease
-------------------------------------------------------------
A bacterial vine disease discovered in 2010 has now infected 1070 orchards representing almost a third of all orchards and just over 40 percent of all New Zealand kiwifruit acreage. It will likely spread to all other orchards in the country.

Of the infected orchards, 38 percent are green kiwifruit orchards, 51 percent gold orchards and the balance new varieties. Green kiwifruit hasn’t been hit as hard by PSA as gold kiwifruit. New Zealand gold production is expected to be down 32 percent this [2012] season, but green production should be down just 10 percent.

The Zespri Gold, also known as Hort16A, the dominant gold kiwifruit variety licensed by Zespri, is highly susceptible to PSA. “It is clear that in the future Hort16A in high-PSA environments is unsustainable,” Michele Hoard, Zespri, said. A new gold variety, the Gold3, which is much more resistant to PSA, is expected to eventually replace much of the lost acreage.

[Byline: Andy Nelson]

